<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Buildings: Properties and Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Understanding Height, Block Height, Y Offset, Style Index, and Facet Flags.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        All facets (except cables) share a common set of properties that control their appearance,
        height, position, and behavior. These properties are set in the <Bold>Add Facets</Bold>
        window before drawing on the map, and can be bulk-edited later for multiple facets at once.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- HEIGHT -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Height (Quarter Storeys)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Height</Bold> value specifies how tall the facet is, measured in
        <Bold>quarter storeys</Bold> (abbreviated as <Bold>QS</Bold>). This measurement system
        is used consistently throughout Urban Chaos for vertical distances.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Quarter Storey Scale
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        One storey in Urban Chaos equals <Bold>4 quarter storeys</Bold>. This gives you fine-grained
        control over vertical dimensions:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>1 QS</Bold> = Quarter storey (one unit of vertical height)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>4 QS</Bold> = 1 storey
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>8 QS</Bold> = 2 storeys
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>12 QS</Bold> = 3 storeys
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>16 QS</Bold> = 4 storeys
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, if you set <Bold>Height = 8</Bold>, the facet will be 2 storeys tall.
        A value of <Bold>Height = 6</Bold> creates a facet that is 1.5 storeys tall.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Height = 4</Bold> creates a standard 1-storey wall suitable for most buildings.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Height = 2</Bold> creates a half-height wall or barrier.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Height = 12</Bold> creates a tall 3-storey wall for large buildings.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- BLOCK HEIGHT -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Block Height
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Block Height</Bold> defines how tall a single storey is <Bold>for texture mapping
        purposes</Bold>. It controls how textures are scaled vertically on the facet.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        In most cases, you should leave Block Height at <Bold>4</Bold> (the default). This matches
        the standard storey size and displays textures at their intended scale.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How Block Height Works
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Block Height allows you to stretch or shrink texture mapping independent of the actual
        physical height of the facet. This is useful for advanced effects like capping pieces,
        parapets, and decorative trim.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Stretching Textures (Block Height &gt; 4)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you set <Bold>Block Height = 8</Bold>, the engine treats each storey as if it were
        2 storeys tall for texture purposes. This effectively <Bold>stretches</Bold> the textures
        vertically.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Example: A facet with <Bold>Height = 4</Bold> (nominally 1 storey) and
        <Bold>Block Height = 8</Bold> will show a stretched texture — the texture is expanded
        to cover 2 storeys of visual height even though the physical facet is only 1 storey tall.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Shrinking Textures (Block Height &lt; 4)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you set <Bold>Block Height = 2</Bold>, the engine treats each storey as if it were
        half a storey tall for texture purposes. This effectively <Bold>shrinks</Bold> the textures
        vertically.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Example: A facet with <Bold>Height = 4</Bold> and <Bold>Block Height = 2</Bold> will show
        2 full texture tiles stacked vertically instead of 1 — the texture is compressed to fit
        half the expected height.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Special Case: Block Height = 1
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Setting <Bold>Block Height = 1</Bold> shows only the <Bold>top 25%</Bold> of the texture.
        This is different from <Bold>Height = 1</Bold> (which shows texture from the bottom).
        Block Height = 1 is useful for thin capping pieces at the top of walls.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>For 99% of use cases, leave Block Height at 4. Only modify it when you need specialized texture scaling effects like decorative trim, parapets, or capping pieces on building tops.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- Y OFFSET -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Y Offset
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Y Offset</Bold> specifies how high off the ground the facet should be drawn,
        measured in <Bold>quarter storeys</Bold>. This allows you to stack facets vertically
        on top of existing structures.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Use Cases
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Y Offset = 0</Bold> — Ground level. Use this for the first layer of any building.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Y Offset = 4</Bold> — One storey up. Use this to stack a second layer on top
                of a 1-storey structure.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Y Offset = 8</Bold> — Two storeys up. Use this for the third layer of a
                multi-storey building.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Stacking Example
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To create a 3-storey building:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Draw the first layer with <Bold>Height = 4, Y Offset = 0</Bold>
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Draw the second layer with <Bold>Height = 4, Y Offset = 4</Bold>
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Draw the third layer with <Bold>Height = 4, Y Offset = 8</Bold>
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Each layer forms its own closed polygon, and the Auto-Build system will detect and process
        each one independently.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Warehouse Stacking:</Run>
                <Run>Always make the first layer of a warehouse exactly 4 QS (1 storey) so doors fit correctly. Doors cannot span multiple storeys. If you need additional height, create a second facet group with Y Offset = 4 and stack it on top.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- STYLE INDEX -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Style Index
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Style Index</Bold> refers to a predefined texture pattern in the
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">style.tma</Run> file. Each style entry
        is a "recipe" that defines which textures to use, their rotations, and how they are
        arranged on the facet.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        How Style Index Works
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When you set <Bold>Style Index = 1</Bold>, the facet uses the first style recipe in
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">style.tma</Run>. <Bold>Style Index = 2</Bold>
        uses the second recipe, and so on.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Add Facets</Bold> window shows a <Bold>texture preview</Bold> of the selected
        style so you can visually see what pattern will be applied before drawing on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Editing Styles
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To create or modify style recipes, use the <Bold>Style Editor</Bold> (a separate
        application in the Darcis Shield toolkit). The Style Editor lets you:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Create new texture patterns by arranging tiles in a grid
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Assign rotation values to individual tiles
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Save the style file and immediately use it in the Map Editor
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Export the style to the game's texture folder for in-game testing
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- FLAGS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Flags are binary properties that modify facet behavior. Multiple flags can be enabled
        on a single facet. Some flags are automatically set or greyed out depending on the
        facet type and building type.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Flag Descriptions
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Invisible</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The facet is not rendered visually but still exists as collision geometry. Useful for
        invisible barriers or hidden collision walls.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Inside</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        Marks this as an interior wall, viewed from inside a building. This flag is automatically
        set for warehouse interior walls and affects texture mapping (uses the "inside" texture
        variant).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">DLit (Dynamically Lit)</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The facet responds to in-game dynamic lighting (e.g., streetlights, explosions, muzzle
        flashes). Without this flag, the facet uses only static baked lighting.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Hug Floor</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The facet automatically snaps to the floor/ground altitude regardless of terrain height
        or surrounding building heights. You do not need to manually specify the Y Offset value.
        Useful for walls on uneven terrain.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Electrified</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        Touching the facet causes the player to be electrocuted and take damage. Used for
        electric fences, exposed wiring, and dangerous barriers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Two Sided</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        By default, facet textures are only rendered on the front side (backface culling saves
        memory and improves performance). Enabling this flag renders textures on <Bold>both
        front and back</Bold> sides of the facet. Useful for thin walls or freestanding barriers
        viewed from multiple angles.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Unclimbable</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        Usually enabled by default. The facet cannot be climbed like a ladder or fence. Disable
        this flag to make a wall climbable.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">On Building</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        Same as <Bold>Hug Floor</Bold>, but specifically for fences. The fence automatically
        snaps to the building/terrain height.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Barb Top</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The facet can be climbed, but cannot be jumped over or vaulted. Used for fences with
        barbed wire or spikes on top.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">See Through</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The player's camera can see through the facet. Useful for chain-link fences, grates,
        or other transparent barriers. The facet still provides collision but allows visibility.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Open</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        Used exclusively for <Bold>gates</Bold>. This flag is set at runtime via mission files
        to open the gate. You typically leave this unchecked in the editor — the mission script
        will enable it when triggered by gameplay events.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Two-Textured</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        The facet is part of an indoor/outdoor texture pairing. This flag is <Bold>automatically
        set</Bold> for warehouse buildings and ensures the correct inside/outside texture variants
        are applied to doors and walls.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,0,0,1">Fence Cut</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,6">
        <Bold>Unused.</Bold> Originally intended for wire cutter objects to open fences, but
        this feature was never implemented in the final game.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Summary
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Understanding these properties gives you complete control over facet appearance and behavior:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Height</Bold> controls physical vertical size (measured in quarter storeys)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Block Height</Bold> controls texture scaling (usually leave at 4)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Y Offset</Bold> controls vertical position for stacking
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Style Index</Bold> selects a texture recipe from
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">style.tma</Run>
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Flags</Bold> modify behavior (lighting, collision, visibility, etc.)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        For most building tasks, you'll primarily use Height, Y Offset, and Style Index. The other
        properties are available for advanced scenarios and fine-tuning.
    </Paragraph>

</FlowDocument>
